### Joint committees

These committees, composed of members from both chambers, were intended to foster cooperation and efficiency, a noble goal that often proved elusive in a deeply divided Congress.

*   [Enrolled Bills](/United_States_Congress_Joint_Committee_on_Enrolled_Bills) (Chairman: Rep. [Thomas G. Davidson](/Thomas_G._Davidson))
*   [The Library](/United_States_Congress_Joint_Committee_on_the_Library) (Chairman: Rep. [William H. Dimmick](/William_H._Dimmick))
*   [Printing](/United_States_Congress_Joint_Committee_on_Printing) (Chairman: Rep. [Samuel A. Smith](/Samuel_A._Smith))

## Caucuses

The formal and informal gatherings of party members, known as caucuses, were vital for coordinating legislative strategy and maintaining party discipline—or, in this era, for attempting to maintain it in the face of centrifugal forces.

*   [Democratic](/House_Democratic_Caucus) (House)
*   [Democratic](/Senate_Democratic_Caucus) (Senate)

## Employees

Behind the scenes, a cadre of dedicated, or at least employed, individuals kept the wheels of the legislative branch turning, performing the necessary administrative tasks that allowed the elected officials to engage in their often-dramatic debates. One might argue their contributions to stability were far more significant than many of the politicians they served.

